notation (e.g. `@module.decorator()`).

commit.message:
Only run selected checks (#147)

We previously always ran all of our checks regardless of the configured
style guide (the set of selected and ignore error codes). Now, we build
our list of visitor classes based on which error codes they can emit and
which error codes are selected in the current style guide.

This is a (minor) performance optimization for folks who have many files
and only a subset of our checks enabled.

Recognize __class_getitem__ as a class method (#145)

According to PEP 560:

> The __class_getitem__ is automatically a class method and does not
> require @classmethod decorator (similar to __init_subclass__) and is
> inherited like normal attributes.

Classify this name the same way we do `__new__` and `__init_subclass__`.

commit.message:
Improve known metaclass base class detection

We previously only looked for known metaclass base classes that were
inheriting using the simple `ast.Name` syntax:

    class Meta(type): pass
    class Meta(ABCMeta): pass

We weren't accounting for the `ast.Attribute` syntax:

    class Meta(abc.ABCMeta): pass

This second syntax will now also match `ABCMeta` and be recognized as a
metaclass base class.

We could alternatively add `abc.ABCMeta` to METACLASS_BASES and
construct the fully-qualified name of each base class that uses the
`ast.Attribute` syntax. The simpler approach used here is currently
unambiguous, so we'll start with this.

commit.message:
Treat "acronym" imports as their own error code (#133)

While not the recommended style, in practice, it is common for CamelCase
names from some packages to be imported as acronyms. Some examples:

    from BeautifulSoup import BeautifulSoup as BS
    from xml.etree.ElementTree import ElementTree as ET

We still consider these naming errors but now use a dedicated code
(N817) so that users can selectively enable or disable this rule
separate from N814 ("camelcase imported as constant").

commit.message:
Don't offset lineno when reporting errors for Python >= 3.8

In Python 3.8, bpo-33211 addressed what is considered a bug where a
function or a class with a decorator would report an incorrect `lineno`
and `col_offset`.  In versions < 3.8, the first decorator line was
reported, which requires the accounted for offset.  Now, the actual
`lineno` and `col_offset` is reported by the `ast` module.

Please see https://bugs.python.org/issue33211 for reference.

commit.message: Prepare the 0.9.0 release

Recognize Python 3.8's args.posonlyargs group

`args.posonlyargs` was added to Python 3.8's AST to represent
position-only arguments. These comes first in the total ordering of a
function's argument groups, so we need to consider them inside of
get_arg_name_tuples().

This is particularly relevant to N805, which checks the name of the
first argument for methods.
